olitical position one must occupy in order to take the risk to speak truthfully. These lectures—carefully edited and including notes and introductory material to fully illuminate Foucault’s insights—are a major addition to Foucault’s English language corpus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFreedom of speech. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aacademic, scholarly, research, professor, university, college, lectures, famous person, thinker, grenoble, berkeley, 1980s, history, historical, greek, truth, speech, discourse, rome, greece, christian, christianity, religion, religious, faith, belief, socratic, socrates, freedom, language, philosophy, philosopher, historian, interdisciplinary, political.1 aFoucault, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFruchaud, Henri-Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGros, Frédéric.1 aLorenzini, Daniele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLuxon, Nancy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226509631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226509631/original  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles